<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>NYT &gt; Technology</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/section/technology</link><description>Technology industry news, commentary, and analysis, with reporting on big tech, startups, and internet culture. The New York Times is a hub for conversation about news and ideas.</description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/Technology.xml" type="application/rss+xml" /><item><title>How Meta’s Threads Became as Popular as X</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/05/technology/threads-meta-twitter-x.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/05/technology/threads-meta-twitter-x.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/05/technology/threads-meta-twitter-x.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The social platform that Meta once positioned as a rival to Elon Musk’s X now has 500 million monthly users. It increasingly resembles Reddit.</description><dc:creator>Eli Tan</dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 05 Jul 2026 09:01:42 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Threads</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Instagram</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Facebook</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark E Zuckerberg</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">X</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/30/multimedia/META-THREADS-1-03-tgph/META-THREADS-1-03-tgph-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Ian C. Bates for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>“We want to be the largest and best platform for public conversation,” said Connor Hayes, the head of Threads. </media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Judge Temporarily Pauses Paramount-Warner Bros. Deal</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/20/business/media/paramount-warner-bros-deal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/20/business/media/paramount-warner-bros-deal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/20/business/media/paramount-warner-bros-deal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The delay is intended to give the court time to consider a lawsuit that argues the $111 billion merger violates antitrust laws.</description><dc:creator>David McCabe</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 20 Jul 2026 17:23:59 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Paramount Pictures</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mergers and Acquisitions</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Rob Bonta</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/20/multimedia/20biz-paramount-cgbh/20biz-paramount-cgbh-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Mark Abramson for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>The Warner Bros. studio in Burbank, Calif.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Meta in Talks to Lease Computing Power to Anthropic in Potential $10 Billion Deal</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/17/technology/meta-anthropic-ai-computing-power.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/17/technology/meta-anthropic-ai-computing-power.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/17/technology/meta-anthropic-ai-computing-power.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A deal would underline how scarce computing power is for artificial intelligence development, and could create a new business for Meta.</description><dc:creator>Eli Tan and Mike Isaac</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 17 Jul 2026 16:17:06 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Data center</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Startup</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Enterprise Computing</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/17/multimedia/17biz-meta-anthropic-qjkb/17biz-meta-anthropic-qjkb-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Dustin Chambers for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>A data center owned by Meta in Georgia. A deal with Anthropic could potentially alleviate pressure on Meta from investors, who have questioned how much it has been spending on data centers.</media:description></media:content></item></channel></rss>